cards.desc:
How to build Habit Forming Products

How do we influence consumer behaviors?

Hook cycle consists in:

**Trigger**
Prompts the consumer to take action. Advertising, PR, emails are examples of external triggers. At the opposite side there are also internal triggers.

**Action**
Eliminate as many steps as possible. The action needs to be easier than thinking in order to be done.

**Variable reward**
After action give a reward that is variable in order to hook the consumer into a cycle and for a habit.

**Investment**
Ask for a small investment from the consumers and store the value in your product.
We value our work investment. This is called the IKEA Effect
cards.name: [Book] Hooked – Nir Eyal

John Maxwell describes this book as one of the 5 best book ever read.

This book looks at exemplary leadership.

5 practices that all leaders have:

1. Model the way
2. Inspire a shared vision
3. Challenge the process
4. Enable others to act
5. Encourage the heart

Foundation of credibility. Leaders have credibility. It's the foundation of leadership.

20 characteristics. Which 7 do you want to have in the leader? The most picked 4 are:

1. Honest 
2. Forward looking
3. Competent
4. Inspiring

Do what you say you will do. **DWYSYWD**

Vision + Challenge. A leader has an inspiring vision, they are audacious and inspiring. The challenge is a requirement to getting the best out of us.

cards.desc:
An interesting book on the journey to building a company and the incremental path the owner took.

While there are things that I liked in the book there was also one that was very annoying - the use of I throughout the book. It is a book about I, my and myself and I think this paragraph is very descriptive of that:

*If I could go back to the times when I told those filtered stories of everything I did right, I’d talk about the things I speak about now. The things I wrote about in this book.*

I think it is at the border of a Good book but not really there.
cards.name: [Book] Permission to Screw Up: How I Learned to Lead by Doing (Almost) Everything Wrong: Kristen Hadeed, Simon Sinek: 9781591848295: Amazon.com: Books

cards.desc:
The book is a classic and as any classic it is worth investing time.

Yet for the 7h15m(audible time) the invested effort could not be worth especially including and post Competent Level. 

Each chapter ends with a given "law" that is the one thing that matters. It could be actually read backwards - read the last paragraph of the chapter - learn the "law" and then if you think you have any trouble in understanding it or applying it read the entire chapter.

I would recommend it to people with lower emotional intelligence levels, people looking into ways to expand their understanding of relationship management and in general human interactions enthusiasts.
cards.name: [Book] How to Win Friends & Influence People: Dale Carnegie: 8937485909400: Amazon.com: Books

cards.desc:
The book is in a way a shorter summary of the previous books from Dan Ariely.

I am a big fan of Ariely and would highly recommend having read at least one book from him.
On the overall I found the book having some great messages and ideas but I don't think it is one of his best books.

I don't really recommend it.

cards.desc:
The checklist manifesto is a book with nice stories around one simple idea:
Having a checklist before or during important actions are not just improving lifes but also saving them

We humans have flawed decision-makers and have unreliable memories even on expert levels. We will always forget small details and miss important steps.

Checklist seem able to defend anyone against problems. They catch mental flaws inherent in all of us:

* Memory
* Attention
* Thoroughness

Recommended to all levels but I think watching only a summary would be enough: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=18ns58FyPmY

Great stories behind but only interesting for those that are not already sold to the idea that checklist are great for us.
cards.name: [Book] The Checklist Manifesto

cards.desc:
by Jurgen Appelo

"Never forget that better principles, not better practices, are what organizations really need."

A great book on the subject. After finishing quite a lot of articles, books, information on the subject I can say that the book is a good summary to it all. It is a book on motivation, on keeping people engaged and happy. Full of nice Appelo things I would recommend it to mostly everyone interested in the topic.

Convincing managers of the benefits of new ideas is best done by delivering on commitment in order to create trust, always trying to solve your manager's problem first, and experimenting with new ideas in safe-to-fail environments.

Knowing that it is all about how the entire system acts on individuals, and how individuals act on the entire system, has made me more confident and systematic as a project manager and as a change manager. I know that what I need to do is to locally construct just enough boundaries and feedback mechanisms to get going and improve from there. My managers are impressed and I enjoy my work. An identity as ‘the project wizard' has stayed with me.

cards.desc:
The book is about transaction analysis - a system of popular psychology based on the idea that one's behavior and social relationships reflect an interchange between parental (critical and nurturing), adult (rational), and childlike (intuitive and dependent) aspects of personality established early in life.

In the field of psychoanalytic theories, with significant criticism around the subject this book is great because of the fact that it gives perspectives to how we human think and behave. 

The idea that all of us carry with us a Parent, and Adult and a Child and that most dysfunctional communication happends when strange boundaries are crossed (for example a Child speak to an Adult) is something I feel has a lot of logic.

I recommend this book to somebody interested in expanding perspectives on psychology but I don't think this is a manual of how and what a Scrum Master should act.

I would consider it a book for an Advanced-Beginner (maybe) but mostly for a competent Scrum Master.
